42,http://www.armslist.com/posts/4406042,"For Sale:  N82 Tactical Sig Sauer P226/P229 Holster, Professional Model","Lake STL, St. Louis, Missouri",$ 40,"Listed On: Wednesday, August 5, 2015",Holsters,no type,no type,no type,no type,"One of the most comfortable holsters I have ever used, fits P226/P229.  Good condition, sold my Sig a while back so I no longer have any use for it.  Priced for local sale, shipping extra.

The Nate Squared Tactical Professional holster is the ultimate IWB (inside-the-waistband) holster. It has all the comfort of our Original design, but comes with the following additional features: adjustable cant, tuckable, excellent positive retention. The holster is made of polycarbonate, which is an extremely durable thermoplastic. Common uses range from cd's & dvd's to bullet resistant glass. We chose to use polycarbonate because it has 30% more tensile strength and almost double the impact strength of acrylic-polyvinyl chloride, which is the material used by many of the most popular IWB holsters on the market today. All of this simply means that the Professional holster is made of the highest quality materials available. Using polycarbonate also allowed us to develop a positive retention IWB holster with our Twist Release System™.  When the holster is worn, your body puts pressure against the backing, which presses the firearm against the polycarbonate.  The polycarbonate holds the firearm in place and provides additional security for the retention of your firearm.  Simply drive your thumb between the holster and the grip, then slightly twist the grip toward your body to release the trigger guard from the retention bump for a smooth draw!"

55,http://www.armslist.com/posts/4406055,For Sale:  .30-06 hunting rifle with Mauser 98 action and beautiful wood Monte Carlo stock,"Grey Forest (NW of SA), San Antonio, Texas",$ 300,"Listed On: Sunday, June 7, 2015",Rifles,no type,30-06 Springfield                                                                                ,Bolt Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"good .30-06 hunting rifle, manufactured in 1952 in Columbia using a Mauser 98 action. Information about these is a little sketchy, and I'm relating what I can learn about it off the internet, but I encourage you to do your own research and give it a good look if you intend to buy it. I personally have never fired this weapon, but it came to me from the collection of a man who had fired it several times a year for decades, so I believe it to be safe and complete -- and he said, quite accurate.

The 22"" barrel needs to be refinished to make it look its best, but it is serviceable and in good condition otherwise -- not pitted and I can find no rust. The rifling looks good and there is no apparent muzzle erosion.
The action is smooth and tight, and I would guess someone has worked on the trigger because the release is quite crisp.

The scope mounts on the receiver were obviously done by a professional: they are very solid, and the bolt handle has been bent and countoured to pass by the scope's eyepiece. The scope is a Simmons Aetec 2.8-10x44, in good condition with nice clear glass. Shock-corded transparent lens covers are included.

851,http://www.armslist.com/posts/4406851,For Sale/Trade:  Winchester M1917 Rifle,"East Arlington, Jacksonville, Florida",$ 875,"Listed On: Saturday, June 13, 2015",Rifles,Winchester                                                                                ,30-06 Springfield                                                                                ,Bolt Action                                                                                ,Rifle,"I have for sale an extremely hard to find Winchester M1917 rifle - it took me many years to find it. The receiver serial number indicates a September 1917 production, and the barrel is dated the previous month, so it could have even seen service with our boys at Belleau Wood.

The rifle is a post WW1 re-arsenal with Parkerized metal. I believe the stock was likely changed with another Winchester stock at that time, but however it happened, finding a ""W"" stock on a Winchester M1917 is really hard to find. The bore is pitted and was most likely used by a VFW group for parades and funerals where they shot corrosive blanks in gun salutes and didn't clean them afterward. I spent several days cleaning years of buildup and corrosion out of the bore, but finally found some rifling remaining. I've fired it and while I wouldn't shoot a match with it, it still shoots ""minute of Kraut"". Overall, it's a gorgeous sample US rifle from WW1, and even better for the niche collector, it's a true Winchester!
A lot of the parts are ""W"" stamped, including the barrel, bolt, front and rear sights, bayonet lug and stock, but there are several ""non-W"" (non-Winchester) parts including:
- the bolt sleeve (E)
- cocking piece (R)
- buttstock swivel and base (E)
- buttplate (R)
- follower (E)
- lower band swivel (E)
- extractor (E)
I figure the next owner can replace them with ""W"" parts as a restoration project if so desired for not a lot of money.

The price is $875 cash FTF in NE FL, or I'll ship to a C&R or 01 FFL within the continental US for extra $25. If shipping, payment must be via US Postal Money Order. Cross posted on other websites.  Feel free to contact me with any questions.  Additional pictures are available via email."
